06302nam a22008295i 9780774865630DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748656307 a10.59962/97807748656302doi  a(DE-B1597)662069  a(OCoLC)1256450463  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHC447b.G56 2021 7aPOL0240002bisacsh04a338.959822300aGlobalization, Poverty, and Income Inequality :bInsights from Indonesia /ced. by Richard Schwindt, Arianto A. Patunru, Richard Barichello. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b41 charts/diagrams, 28 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAsia Pacific Legal Culture and Globalization00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tForeword -- tIndonesia -- tGlobalization and Inequality -- tTrade Expansion in Indonesia -- tIs Globalization Associated with Income Inequality? -- tA Child’s Growth Is a Nation’s Growth -- tReducing Rural Poverty through Trade? -- tIs Greater Openness to Trade Good? -- tCoffee Eco-Certification -- tUnderstanding Visual Disability as Development and Global Human Rights Issues -- tUrban Property Rights -- tIndonesia -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe process of globalization has implications for human rights, though the relationship between the two is not always clear. How does globalization effect human rights in local contexts? Globalization, Poverty, and Income Inequality examines the relationships between globalization and trade liberalization, and poverty and income inequality, using Indonesia as a case study. This empirically rigorous investigation finds that although increased trade tends to reduce poverty, there are exceptions. For example, globalization via trade in certified organic coffee has not helped low-income farmers. And globalized access to treatments for visual problems has been countermanded by rising digitization that negatively affects the visually disabled poor. Ultimately, the chapters describe an ambiguous relationship between trade liberalization and inequality, both of which can increase or decrease in proportion to one another depending on region and sector. This empirically driven work provides a nuanced view of the trade-poverty relationship, contributing balanced testimony to policy debates being held internationally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGlobalizationzIndonesia. 0aIncome distributionzIndonesia. 0aPovertyzIndonesia. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Economic Policy.2bisacsh1 aAnanta, Aris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArifin, Bustanul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArifin, Evi Nurvidya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarichello, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarichello, Richard, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBennouna, Cyril, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDartanto, Teguh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, James W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarahap, Faisal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKusumaningrum, Santi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeaf, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcLean, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatunru, Arianto A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPatun